ce:section.ce:para:
When using GPTMS as the fluorescence sensitizer, the contents of the curcumin in actual food samples were determined as described in Section 2.6, which were basically consistent with those by HPLC analysis (Table 1
                        ). The results of one-way ANOVA for the two methods disclosed that there was no significant difference in precision (F < F
                        0.05, 4, 4 = 6.39) and accuracy (P > 0.05) within 95% confidence interval. The recoveries (Table S3) of the studied fourteen food samples were from 96.7% to 104.7% with RSDs from 0.33% to 2.56%. In addition, the recoveries of strawberry, apple, kiwi skin peel and tomato extracts rich in polyphenols but lacking curcumin were also satisfactory (98.2%–103.8%) with RSDs of 0.51–1.54%. GPTMS fluorescence method was characterized of simple operation (adding GPTMS to the sample for vortex), rapid detection (<2 min), low cost (only 80 μL GPTMS and a fluorescence spectrophotometer) and high sensitivity (an LOD of 0.067 ng/mL), and the comparable accuracy (recovery 96.7%–104.7%) as HPLC method in the detection of curcumin in actual food samples. However, HPLC method required a HPLC instrument with consumable HPLC column and mobile phase, and the analysis was done in about 10 min with the LOD of 0.2 μg/mL. The above results demonstrated that GPTMS as the fluorescence sensitizer for the detection of curcumin possessed a good ability to resist matrix interference with good precision, and was a promising method for food analysis.
